## Lessons Learned

- Phishing emails are the most common threat vector for malware infections
- A single phishing campaign can target multiple employees simultaneously
- Always check sender email address carefully — not just display name
- Playbooks save critical time during incident response
- Containment must happen BEFORE eradication — stop the spread first
- PICERL is easy to remember for SANS framework
- NIST combines Containment + Eradication + Recovery into one phase

## Defender's Perspective

- Deploy email filtering and anti-phishing solutions
- Conduct regular phishing awareness training for employees
- Have playbooks ready BEFORE an incident occurs
- EDR on every endpoint enables faster containment
- Regular backups ensure fast recovery after incidents
- Document everything — chain of custody and incident timeline

## Attacker's Perspective (Why This Matters for Pentesting)

- Phishing is the most effective initial access vector
- PDF attachments are commonly trusted by users
- Understanding IR helps pentesters know how quickly defenders respond
- Faster IR = shorter attacker dwell time = less damage possible

